- The quality of the AC/heat
- The quality of the kitchen
- the reputation of the schools
- the size of the yard (had to be non-zero in size usually)
Those 4 were the most important. Usually if any two of those were "very bad" they would pick the other house.

strategy: The most important and non-negotiable factor in the Prolific user's choices between homes in Section 1 is the quality of the school system. This buyer will accept nothing less than a moderate school system, but prefers that the school system be very good or good. If the school system is at least moderate, then this buyer considers other beneficial factors such as the size of the home and the yard and also the age of the home. Size of the home is the next most important factor after the school system quality. This buyer prefers a the newer of the two homes if possible, but will choose the older one if the older one is larger, has a larger yard, and then if it has a newer heat/AC system or a very good kitchen. Proximity to the park is also a plus but not a deal breaker. If the school system is very good, good, or moderate and some of the previously mentioned factors such as house size are compelling to the buyer, then this buyer is willing to put up with the home with the higher level of noise pollution and/or traffic. In sum, the quality of the school system must be at least moderate in order for this buyer to even consider buying a particular home. This buyer will buy a home with a moderate school system over a home with a very good or good school system if the home has some really excellent qualities otherwise. This buyer does not worry about a bad heat/AC system or a bad kitchen because these can be fixed if the home is bought at the right price whereas the school system cannot be changed.
strategy2: No my previous description of the Prolific user's buying strategy would remain the same. The most important factor was the quality of the school system followed by other factors of varying importance. Anything below an at least moderate school system was unacceptable to this buyer.

strategy:
They needed a HVAC system that was at least moderate, better if it was higher quality. They wouldn't even consider homes that didn't pass that bar.

Beyond that, they were most interested in the best quality kitchen and the largest home size, assuming the home had at least SOME yard. If the home had no yard, the home had to excel in other metrics, or the alternative had to particularly fail in other metrics in order for them to consider it.

The remaining metrics were rather unimportant, though if they remained undecided after the above considerations, they favored low traffic noise and a school rating that was at least not very bad.
strategy2: I haven't been given any reason to change my assessment of their strategy. I thought it was nuanced from the beginning, and incorporated several of the decision strategies described. I still think that.
metastrategy:
Early on, for each choice, I paid most attention to quality extremes for each metric to see what they might be reacting against or in favor of. That gave me an outline of their most important features, and which ones they consider mandatory.

Then I hypothesized a series of more refined theories based on patterns of choice, and paid particular attention to when their choices "broke" the theory I was working with. I then either refined or abandoned it, depending on the circumstances.

Eventually, I zeroed in on a theory that had a high rate of success in predicting decisions.

strategy: This was confusing to figure out. As I watched each Prolific user make a choice, I wondered what they were basing their decision on. A few times, I thought it was the size of the house, the traffic flow or the noise. It was inconsistent and did not give me a pattern to their choices. I thought perhaps they were basing it on the reputation of the schools, but then some of them didn't seem to care about this. I also was surprised to see that some didn't place value on the condition of the kitchen nor the quality of the heating systems. They also didn't always choose the larger house nor the larger property size. I think the the user made random decisions based on which house had the more positives. They didn't seem to target into one category.
strategy2: I still believe that the user weighed each category and zeroed in on the ones that meant the most to them. Although they cared about each thing, they took the ones that they cared about the most, gave them the most weight in the decision and then made their final decision.
metastrategy: I don't know for sure, but I feel that they made their decisions based on a few of the categories and not the entire list. I think they cared about everything but realize that you can't have perfection when deciding on a house. you have to concentrate on the things that will help you make the best decision.

binatts_comp2_description: Person description: When making his choices between homes in Section 1, Joe cared about three features: the year the building was built, the closeness to public transportation, and the size of the yard. He considered the difference between the two homes on each feature (e.g. a 100 sq. ft. yard versus a 400 sq. ft. yard = a 300 sq. ft. difference), and then weighed those differences together
strategy:
The Prolific user prioritized their choices depending on the size of the house per square feet. A significant amount of time they tended to select the bigger house. 

However, how much negatives there were to positive traits also influenced their decision. For instance, if a house carried a lot more "bad" and "very bad" qualities, the Prolific user would tend to choose the option with better qualities, but only if the size of the house was not sacrificed (give or take 300-400 sq ft avg). If both house options had an equal number of bad traits, the Prolific user would choose the bigger house. Additionally, if the size of a house was bigger by >600 sq ft, the user would choose that bigger house option regardless of whether there were many cons to pros.

Reputation of the schools and park distance did not matter at all to this user.

Overall, I believe the Prolific user first determined how big the houses were, then how many "bad" and "very bad" qualities were listed, and assessed whether those bad qualities were numerous enough to sway a decision. If the bad qualities were relatively the same amount, or the house size difference was significant, the user would almost always choose the bigger house.
strategy2:
My description has not really changed, but I think the strategies and questions this study provides does not fully describe the user's strategy. 

I would describe it as the Prolific user having the single most deciding factor, which is house size, and then comparing the rest of the traits if the size difference is worth bearing the number of negatives. The rest of the other traits' description would not significantly matter, as the kitchen could be very bad quality or the AC/heating unit could be bad etc. 

For example, if a moderately larger house had two "bad" qualities vs a smaller house with one "bad" quality, the Prolific user would choose the larger house. 

However, if a moderately larger house had a majority bad qualities vs a smaller house, the Prolific user would choose the smaller house.

An exception is when the house is significantly larger, such as by over 600 sq ft, that regardless of a majority of bad qualities the user would choose the larger house.
metastrategy: I knew there was one single trait the Prolific user valued the most, which is house size.

feedback: It took much longer than expected.

strategy: I think the Prolific user looked at the size of the home first and then went down the list of pros and cons from there.  It did not seem that school reputation mattered much so this user may not have school age children.  It seemed like the A/C condition and the kitchen condition were important factors.  I saw some choices where the small home was picked because the larger one had very bad A/C units and kitchens.  After A/C and kitchen, I think traffic and noise pollution were important factors after that.  It seemed like some of the choices were similar and the person went with the choice with less traffic or noise pollution.  So I think this user leaned towards the larger homes, but if there were too many cons for the larger ones, then the smaller ones were picked to have a better quality of life.  After all, what use is living in a large house if the A/C doesn't work or the kitchen is awful?
strategy2: I think this user considered the home size as most important and then considered the other features such as A/C and kitchen quality as well as noise pollution and traffic.  So I think home size was most important. Then A/C and kitchen quality were next most important.  Finally, the noise pollution and traffic features were the third most important to this user.  I think my description is about the same as before.  Seeing the different choice styles made a lot of sense.  I think this user really thought about a lot of different aspects of the home choices and made decisions based on those thoughts.
metastrategy: I think this user contemplated several features of the home choices and used those to make their decisions.  This user did not have an all-or-nothing approach that was described in some of the types of decisions that exist.  I think this user weighed each feature that was important to them against the other features and made decisions that way.  It seemed like home size was the most important feature with A/C and kitchen condition being next in importance.  Noise pollution and traffic seemed to be third-most important for this user.

strategy:
The priority seemed to be on the quietest house/area they could find. The second priority seemed to be least traffic. The third looked like proximity to parks. The noise was the most consistent factor when choosing a house, and as long as it was better than the other choice, was most often the house picked to rent. The general strategy looked like get the quietest house, and then with the best traffic and a reasonable distance to a park, but sometimes it seemed like the renter wanted to maximize those three areas, so if there was a bad noise rating, they might choose that house anyway if the other two qualities were clearly much better. 

I couldn't find much pattern in choices when it came to school quality, size of house and yard, age of house, quality of kitchen and HVAC. Those all seemed lower priority, if they mattered at all, when compared to the noise rating, and then the traffic and parks. The only thing I noticed was the renter seemed to go against all of their preferences if one of the two houses appeared much better in a lot of the categories.

There were a few instances that were outliers, that went against the priority categories and didn't seem to offer much better choices in the other house, but it was chosen anyway. I put very little weight on those.
strategy2: I don't think my description would change at all. They put the most value on the three categories I mentioned, with the most weight on noise pollution. I couldn't find any obvious patterns or preferences for the rest of the categories.
metastrategy: I jotted down a few notes for the first 15-20 selections of houses and started to look for patterns. Then I just observed and tried to predict which houses the user would choose before the button turned green. With some elimination of the unimportant categories, a general strategy started to emerge, which I feel is mostly correct.

feedback: Not sure what you were looking for, but burying me in a long string of pairwise choices was extremely difficult to work with. strategy:
There are two things I noticed when evaluating the choices, the two most important things to the user was the size of the home and the kitchen quality. It also seemed like the year it was built and school reputation was also important, but there were many times when it did not seem like it mattered. 

They will generally always choose the property with the biggest space unless the two homes were close in size. If the sizes of the two homes were only a difference of say 200-400 square feet, they would look at kitchen quality next and make their choice. I also noticed that if the square foot was below 800, they ignored it completely, which made me assume that's their baseline as to how big they want their home. I came to that conclusion because there were a few times they chose the biggest house but had the worst specs in every category, which told me they valued size over everything. 

The things they cared about the least were the park distance, noise level, traffic, yard, and AC/Heating. However, it did come into play when the home size and kitchen were very similar in specs. Other than that, I was able to guess with a 95% accuracy on what the user was going to pick next based on the home size and kitchen quality.
strategy2: My description has not changed one bit, in fact, it actually felt validated after reading the following materials on the different strategies. The user definitely applied one of those strategies in their decision making and it totally makes sense. I still believe they chose home size and kitchen quality as their two biggest specs they were looking for.
metastrategy: I can't say I know what the user's process was 100%, but I have a pretty good guess as to what they were choosing, because it was a obvious pattern. I actually covered up the answers for each test and made a guess of my own based on the pattern I saw. I got most of them correct, which told me my thesis was most likely on point; therefore, I am quite confident that they were choosing home size and kitchen quality.
attention_check: I will complete this study with my full attention.
permission: Yes, I am okay with my answers to these questions
feedback: I think it took me a little longer than expected because I was actually testing myself to see if I found out the pattern. Other than that, I think it was fine!

strategy:
I think they valued:
Home size - between 600 and 1800, slightly weighted towards the higher number
Yard size - between 50 and 500
But prefered home size 3x the yard size or greater.

I did not see significant preference expressed on other items like school quality, kitchens, and etc.
strategy2:
My perception is that the person had three variables they considered: home size, yard size, home age. 
I think the person preferred the biggest home that came with a non-zero sized yard, but not necesarily the largest 600 sq.ft. yard.  And as a very weak preference, I think the person newer to older homes.  
There seemed no preference for the other variables.  

In summary, my opinion has not changed, except so as to add a weak preference for newer rather than older.  But the frameworks given did help, and I think the strategy used is best described by the last one presented to me, which I believe was framework "F".
metastrategy:
I made a best guess. The respondent's answers did not seem completely consistent.  I simplified by looking at just the two variables that seemed most correlated to me in what the person was doing.  This led to simpler projections for me of what was steering the person's choices.  But I recognize they may have been valuing more variables than what I was baselining off of, and the tradeoffs there were too subtle for me to discern. 
To summarize, I looked for what seemed the most relevant variables to their choices and baselined what I thought they were doing off of that.  This was perhaps a simplification for me... which may not have grasped their opinions of less dominant variables driving their choices.
